        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1962-11-29T18:11:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1962-11-29T18:11:00-05:00" n="333"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d333">
                <head>333. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in the United Kingdom</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d333fn0">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 745C.00/11-2962. Confidential; Limit Distribution. Drafted by Mathews
                        on November 23; cleared by <persName corresp="#p_BWCJ1">Burdett</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_SJJ1">Sisco</persName>, Furnas, and <persName
                            corresp="#p_MGGC2">McGhee</persName> (in substance); and approved by
                            <persName corresp="#p_THJ1">Tasca</persName>. Repeated to
                        Salisbury.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1962-11-29T18:11:00-05:00">November 29, 1962, 6:11 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2830. Inform appropriate <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> officials that US
                    representatives will wish discuss during December 4-5 African talks possibility
                    of more effective <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> and US roles re Southern
                    Rhodesia if <persName corresp="#p_WE4">Whitehead</persName> wins substantial
                    victory in December 14 elections. US believes that in new situation following
                    coming into force of new constitution and elections, <gloss target="#t_UK1"
                        >UK</gloss> and US may be able help bridge gap between <persName
                        corresp="#p_WE4">Whitehead</persName>’s government and African nationalists.
                    Important element of such effort would be provision increased training
                    opportunities to prepare more Africans for participation in government
                    activities. This should ease way to more expeditious expansion of African
                    participation in government which US considers essential to orderly political
                    progress in Southern Rhodesia and to continuation of at least economic ties
                    between three components of Federation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RD3">
                            <hi rend="strong">Rusk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
